  "prompt": "What does \"natural causality\" mean?",
  "response": "\"Natural causality\" refers to the concept that events in the natural world occur due to inherent, observable, and predictable cause-and-effect relationships. This term is often used in the context of scientific and philosophical discussions to describe how natural phenomena are governed by laws of nature, such as gravity, thermodynamics, and other physical principles, rather than by supernatural or non-natural forces.\n\nIn essence, natural causality suggests that every event has a preceding cause that can be understood and explained through empirical observation and rational analysis. This concept is fundamental to the scientific method, which seeks to uncover these natural causes through experimentation and evidence-based reasoning.",
